<p>Refer to the guidance on this page if you want to:</p>
<ul>
  <li>write messages that work well on different channels</li>
  <li>choose wording that patients understand and can act upon</li>
  <li>make content inclusive and accessible for a wide range of patients</li>
  <li>find examples and templates to reference when writing your message</li>
</ul>
<p>This guidance was developed with input from clinical safety, governance and delivery teams across NHS England. It brings together established writing standards and findings from user research into how NHS messages are read and interpreted.</p>
<p>It sits alongside the Messaging Best Practice website so teams can plan, write and send messages in a joined-up and consistent way.</p>

<h2 id="writing-effective-messages">Writing effective messages</h2>
<p>Always consider the needs of the patient and the channel you are using when writing your message. Each channel has its own benefits for both the person receiving it and the sender.</p>
<p>General guidance for writing messages in any channel include:</p>
<ul>
  <li>keep messages short and concise</li>
  <li>put whatever matters most first</li>
  <li>use short, descriptive titles or subject lines</li>
  <li>include a call to action when needed</li>
  <li>only include links when they are necessary and have a clear purpose</li>
  <li>personalise your message appropriately for the channel and message type</li>
  <li>use plain simple English and follow the NHS content guide for tone and voice</li>
</ul>

<p><a href="https://service-manual.nhs.uk/content/voice-and-tone" title="External website">Read the NHS content guide for voice and tone</a>.</p>

<h2 id="how-to-write-for-different-channels">How to write for different channels</h2>

<p>To make your message more effective consider the following.<p/>

<h4 id="the-language-you-use-should-reflect-the-message-type">The language you use should reflect the message type</h4>
<p>For example, the language you use for an invitation to a patient’s first screening appointment will be different to that of communicating test results. Always consider the impact your message will have on the person reading it when writing your message.</p>

<h4 id="different-channels-require-different-content">Different channels require different content</h4>
<p>For example, copying and pasting the contents of a letter into an App message may not be the best choice. Always consider the user experience when writing a message for more than one channel.</p>

<h4 id="the-accessibility-and-inclusion-needs-of-your-users">The accessibility and inclusion needs of your users</h4>
<p>Digital channels can easily link to further information or next steps, whereas paper letters require patients to type a printed URL into a web browser for the same information. A paper letter is accessible for visually impaired users preferring large print or braille, while digital channels might be preferred by users of assistive technology. </p>

<h4 id="the-length-of-your-message">The length of your message</h4>
<p>A single text message has 160 characters so a longer message may require more than one text. This will increase the cost of sending your message. An App message (maximum 5,000 characters) or an email (unlimited characters) might be more suitable for longer messages with more details.</p>

<h2 id="nhs-app-messages">NHS App messages</h2>

<p>The NHS App is a free and secure way to communicate with patients and the public.</p>
<p>Writing messages specifically for the channel means users are more likely to understand and respond to important health-related requests or advice. You should consider the following when writing messages for the App.<p/>

<h3 id="greeting-app">Greeting</h3>
<p>Patients are more likely to engage with a message that’s relevant and clearly meant for them. If you start your message with a greeting you should use ‘Dear [name]’ and not ‘Hi’ or similar.</p>
<p>Choose which name to use depending on the context of the message. Use their first name when you want to be more encouraging and conversational. For a more serious and reassuring tone you should consider using a person’s title (if they have one) and their last name or their full name.</p>
<p>For example:</p>
<ul>
  <li>conversational tone - ‘Dear Jane’</li>
  <li>reassuring tone - ‘Dear Mrs Smith’ or ‘Dear Jane Smith’</li>
</ul>
<p>Avoid using just a surname or first name without a greeting as it sounds impersonal (except when sending a text message – see Text messages).</p>

<h3 id="protecting-people-from-spam-and-phishing-app">Protecting people from spam and phishing</h3>
<p>To access messages in the App, patients need to go through NHS login. This means App messages are more secure than email messages or text. Research has shown patients are more likely to trust links in the NHS App, and because the App is secure you can use text links rather than having to write out the full URL as in a text message or email.</p>
<p><a href="https://notify.nhs.uk/using-nhs-notify/links-and-urls" title="External website">How to use text links and URLs in the NHS App</a>.</p>

<h3 id="telling-patients-who-your-message-is-from-app">Telling patients who your message is from</h3>
<p>Patients and the public are more likely to trust a message if they know who sent it. You can choose the sender name that is displayed with your App message when you onboard with NHS Notify. </p>
<p>Your sender name should help recipients quickly identify your service, for example 'NHS vaccines', 'Register with a GP surgery service' or 'Manor View Practice'.</p>
<p><a href="https://notify.nhs.uk/using-nhs-notify/tell-recipients-who-your-messages-are-from#nhs-app-sender-name%22%20HYPERLINK%20%22https://notify.nhs.uk/using-nhs-notify/tell-recipients-who-your-messages-are-from#nhs-app-sender-name" title="External website">Read about how NHS Notify uses sender names</a>.</p>

<h3 id="length-of-message-app">Length of message</h3>
<p>NHS App messages can be up to 5,000 characters, but research shows some patients will only read the first part of the message. Keep your message concise and focused on what is important.</p>
<p>Break longer content into short paragraphs or steps so it’s easy to scan. Put the most important information at the top of the message.</p>

