<h2 id="paper-letters">Paper letters</h2>

<p>Letters allow for longer messages and you can format the text to include headings and bullet points. They are available in large print and braille, which makes them more accessible for some patients. There may also be legal or clinical safety reasons for using letters.</p>
<p>Letters are expensive to send and a digital alternative should always be considered.</p>

<p><a href="https://notify.nhs.uk/pricing-and-commercial/letters" title="External website">Find the cost of sending letters with NHS Notify</a>.</p>

<h3 id="greeting-letters">Greeting</h3>

<p>Letters tend to be more formal so start your message with ‘Dear [full name]’ and not ‘Hi’ or similar. Including a greeting is important as it builds trust.</p>

<h3 id="telling-patients-who-your-message-is-from-letter">Telling patients who your letter is from</h3>

<p>Use your service name at the start of the letter as well as in the signature, so patients can quickly recognise who the letter is from. This should match the name used in your NHS App messages, emails or text messages. Building consistency in your messaging will instil confidence in patients and they are more likely to perform an action or request.</p>

<h3 id="formatting-and-templates-letters">Formatting and templates</h3>

<p>You can format your letter to include bullet points, numbered lists, bold text, headings and more.</p>
<p>If you are using NHS Notify to send your message you can download a letter template, which has further guidance on writing letters.</p>

<p><a href="https://notify.nhs.uk/using-nhs-notify/upload-a-letter" title="External website">Find out more about formatting and letter templates with NHS Notify</a>.</p>

